g.text: Graad Factory of Magnets and Miracles U49: The windows are clear, they've been recently washed. You can see a lorryman's cabin with personal belongings, stickers, insignia...
Perception (Sight): A large metal pendant hangs from the rear view mirror. The pendant features a sun crowned with wavy rays.
Half Light: He was acting tough before. This probably scared him a bit. Who knows when it will come in handy -- a slightly scared racist lorryman?
Encyclopedia: It is the seal of Royalist-era Revachol.
You: Look for a clue about who drives the vehicle.
Half Light: He was acting tough before. This definitely scared him a little, you being here.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Racist-nationalist paraphernalia." He grits his teeth. "Not unusual in this part of town. This is our guy." The lieutenant nods towards the racist lorry driver.
Graad Factory of Magnets and Miracles U49: It's clear this is your guy. Only the March edition of 'Power Man Monthly: The Pure Man's Magazine' is missing. It's clearly the rotund raceman's.
You: "You think this lorry belongs to our tough guy?"
You: What kind of stickers and insignia?
Kim Kitsuragi: "Racist-nationalist paraphernalia." He grits his teeth. "Not unusual in this part of town."
Graad Factory of Magnets and Miracles U49: A lorry stuck in the traffic jam. This big, heavy Graad-made machine is well kept for such an old machine.
You: What about the back seat?
Perception (Sight): The back end of the cabin has a small perch to sleep. Large ashtrays. There are several suns and wheels sown into the curtains.
Perception (Smell): Fumes of heavy fuel oil waft over you, making your eyes sting. The odour mixes with cigarette residue.

Graad Factory of Magnets and Miracles U49: The driver has adorned his space with a substantial collection of peculiar paraphernalia. Proclamations about *honour*, *strength*, and *purity* are glued to various panels.
The driver has adorned the side walls with a substantial collection of racist paraphernalia. Proclamations about *honour*, *strength*, and *purity* are glued to various panels.
Conceptualization: A book with ragged edges catches your notice. The front cover features a large, muscular man. The title reads: 'Man from Hjelmdall in the Lost City of the Pygmies'.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Likely, yes. This guy's proud of who he is. Drapes it all over his machine."
Composure: There he is, in front of Frittte, smoking nervously. Hoping it's over.
